SIMPLE: small
RECORDS: 4

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Small
<hw>Small</hw> <pr>(sm⟦add⟧l)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos>
<amorph>[<pos>Compar.</pos> <adjf>Smaller</adjf>
<pr>(sm⟦add⟧l"⟦etil⟧r)</pr>; <pos>superl.</pos>
<adjf>Smallest</adjf>.]</amorph> <ety>[OE. <ets>small</ets>, AS.
<ets>smael</ets>; akin to D. <ets>smal</ets> narrow, OS. & OHG.
<ets>smal</ets> small, G. <ets>schmal</ets> narrow, Dan. & Sw.
<ets>smal</ets>, Goth. <ets>smals</ets> small, Icel. <ets>smali</ets>
small cattle, sheep, or goats; cf. Gr. <grk>mh^lon</grk> a sheep or
goat.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>Having little size, compared with other
things of the same kind; little in quantity or degree; diminutive; not
large or extended in dimension; not great; not much; inconsiderable;
<as>as, a <ex>small</ex> man; a <ex>small</ex> river</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>To compare⟦br⟧
Great things with <qex>small</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Being of slight consequence; feeble in influence or
importance; unimportant; trivial; insignificant; <as>as, a
<ex>small</ex> fault; a <ex>small</ex> business</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>Envincing little worth or ability; not large-minded;
-- sometimes, in reproach, paltry; mean.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>A true delineation of the <qex>smallest</qex> man is capable of
interesting the greatest man.</q> <rj><qau>Carlyle.</qau></rj> <-- the
"g" of "greatest" was a blank in orig. -->⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>Not prolonged in duration; not extended in time;
short; <as>as, after a <ex>small</ex> space</as>.</def>
<rj><au>Shak.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <def>Weak; slender; fine; gentle; soft; not loud.</def>
⟦ldquo⟧A still, <xex>small</xex> voice.⟦rdquo⟧ <rj><au>1 Kings xix.
12.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Great and small</b></col>,<cd>of all ranks or degrees; --
used especially of persons.</cd> ⟦ldquo⟧His quests, <xex>great and
small</xex>.⟦rdquo⟧ <au>Chaucer.</au> -- <col><b>Small arms</b></col>,
<cd>muskets, rifles, pistols, etc., in distinction from cannon.</cd> --
<col><b>Small beer</b></col>. <cd>See under <er>Beer</er>.</cd> --
<col><b>Small coal</b></col>. <sd>(a)</sd> <cd>Little coals of wood
formerly used to light fires</cd>. <au>Gay.</au> <sd>(b)</sd> <cd>Coal
about the size of a hazelnut, separated from the coarser parts by
screening.</cd> -- <col><b>Small craft</b></col> <fld>(Naut.)</fld>,
<cd>a vessel, or vessels in general, of a small size.</cd> --
<col><b>Small fruits</b></col>. <cd>See under <er>Fruit</er>.</cd> --
<col><b>Small hand</b></col>, <cd>a certain size of paper. See under
<er>Paper</er>.</cd> -- <col><b>Small hours</b></col>. <cd>See under
<er>Hour</er>.</cd> -- <col><b>Small letter</b></col>.
<fld>(Print.)</fld>, <cd>a lower-case letter. See <er>Lower-case</er>,
and <cref>Capital letter</cref>, under <er>Capital</er>,
<pos>a.</pos></cd> -- <col><b>Small piece</b></col>, <cd>a Scotch coin
worth about 2⟦frac14⟧d. sterling, or about 4⟦frac12⟧cents.</cd> --
<col><b>Small register</b></col>. <cd>See the Note under 1st
<er>Register</er>, 7.</cd> -- <col><b>Small stuff</b></col>
<fld>(Naut.)</fld>, <cd>spun yarn, marline, and the smallest kinds of
rope.</cd> <au>R. H. Dana, Jr.</au> -- <col><b>Small talk</b></col>,
<cd>light or trifling conversation; chitchat.</cd> -- <col><b>Small
wares</b></col> <fld>(Com.)</fld>, <cd>various small textile articles,
as tapes, braid, tringe, and the like.</cd>
<au>M⟦lsquo⟧Culloch.</au></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Small</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Small
<hw>Small</hw>, <pos>adv.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>In or to small extent,
quantity, or degree; little; slightly.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>
⟦ldquo⟧I wept but <xex>small</xex>.⟦rdquo⟧ <au>Chaucer.</au> ⟦ldquo⟧It
<xex>small</xex> avails my mood.⟦rdquo⟧ <au>Shak.</au>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Not loudly; faintly; timidly.</def> <mark>[Obs. or
Humorous]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>You may speak as <qex>small</qex> as you will.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Small</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Small
<hw>Small</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>The small or slender part
of a thing; <as>as, the <ex>small</ex> of the leg or of the
back</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <pluf>pl.</pluf> <def>Smallclothes.</def>
<mark>[Colloq.]</mark> <rj><au>Hood. Dickens.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <pluf>pl.</pluf> <def>Same as <cref>Little go</cref>. See
under <er>Little</er>, <pos>a.</pos></def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Small</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 4 ====
HEADWORD: Small
<hw>Small</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <def>To make little or less.</def>
<mark>[Obs.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Smallage</ent>⟦br⟧
